Analyzing the Impact of the COVID-19 Pandemic on VT Student Performance¶

The COVID-19 pandemic has significantly transformed the educational landscape for countless students worldwide. As universities rapidly transitioned to remote learning, students found themselves attending Zoom lectures, taking online tests, and submitting digital assignments. This abrupt change in the learning environment has led many to speculate whether the pandemic made college easier, potentially contributing to higher average grade point averages (GPAs). To better understand this phenomenon, we aim to explore the following question and hypothesis:

Central Question: Did online learning lead to an increase in student GPAs during the COVID-19 pandemic? Hypothesis: I propose that, due to the decreased accountability experienced by many students, their academic performance improved during the pandemic compared to pre-pandemic levels.

Dataset: https://udc.vt.edu/irdata/data/courses/grades

Methodology: Utilizing GPA data from Virginia Tech, I will examine the differences in average GPAs across three distinct time periods: pre-pandemic (before Spring 2020), pandemic (between Spring 2020 and Spring 2021), and post-pandemic (after Spring 2021). This analysis will be conducted on both aggregate and course-by-course levels. Subsequently, I will visualize these GPA splits to discern any notable discrepancies between the time periods, calculating the average GPA using the course/time period mean. Furthermore, I will assess the impact of the pandemic on various student demographics' academic experiences by employing a similar method. This will provide a comprehensive understanding of the pandemic's influence on student performance at Virginia Tech.

# Convert the 'Academic Year' column to datetime format
courses['Academic Year'] = pd.to_datetime(courses['Academic Year'], format='%Y-%y')

# Create a datetime object for Spring 2020 and Spring 2021
spring_2020 = pd.to_datetime('2020-01-01')
spring_2021 = pd.to_datetime('2021-01-01')

# Split the dataframe into three dataframes based on academic year and term
courses_before_covid = courses.loc[((courses['Academic Year'] < spring_2020) | 
                            ((courses['Academic Year'] == spring_2020) & (courses['Term'] == 'Fall'))) & 
                            (courses['Term'].isin(['Spring', 'Fall']))]

courses_during_covid = courses.loc[((courses['Academic Year'] >= spring_2020) & (courses['Academic Year'] <= spring_2021)) & 
                            (courses['Term'].isin(['Spring', 'Fall']))]

courses_after_covid = courses.loc[((courses['Academic Year'] > spring_2021) | 
                            ((courses['Academic Year'] == spring_2021) & (courses['Term'] == 'Fall'))) & 
                            (courses['Term'].isin(['Spring', 'Fall']))]

# Calculate the average GPA for each period
avg_gpa_before = courses_before_covid['GPA'].mean()
avg_gpa_during = courses_during_covid['GPA'].mean()
avg_gpa_after = courses_after_covid['GPA'].mean()

# Plot the average GPA for each period
x_labels = ['Before COVID', 'During COVID', 'After COVID']
y_values = [avg_gpa_before, avg_gpa_during, avg_gpa_after]

# Set the style for the plot
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

# Create a line plot with custom markers and colors
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
line_plot = sns.lineplot(x=x_labels, y=y_values, marker='o', markersize=10, linewidth=2, color='blue')

# Customize the plot appearance
ax.set_ylabel('Average GPA', fontsize=14)
ax.set_title('Average GPA Before, During, and After COVID', fontsize=16)
ax.set_ylim(np.min(y_values) - 0.1, np.max(y_values) + 0.1)  # Set y-axis limits

# Annotate data points with their values
for i, value in enumerate(y_values):
    ax.text(i, value + 0.01, f'{value:.2f}', ha='center', fontsize=12, color='black')

# Remove top and right spines for a cleaner look
sns.despine()

plt.show()

Aggregate Insights on Student Performance¶

Upon examining the data, there is a minor difference in academic performance between the pre/post COVID periods and the duration of the COVID pandemic (with a difference of 0.1 and 0.07, respectively). This raises the question of what factors contributed to this shift in GPAs. Was it due to a higher frequency of top grades, or did the typical distribution of GPAs experience an upward shift during the pandemic? To gain a better understanding of these changes, further analysis is needed.

In [5]:
# Calculate the average percentage for each grade category
grade_categories = ['A (%)', 'A- (%)', 'B+ (%)', 'B (%)', 'B- (%)', 'C+ (%)', 'C (%)', 'C- (%)', 'D+ (%)', 'D (%)', 'D- (%)', 'F (%)']
grade_distribution_before = courses_before_covid[grade_categories].mean()
grade_distribution_during = courses_during_covid[grade_categories].mean()
grade_distribution_after = courses_after_covid[grade_categories].mean()

# Prepare data for the grouped bar chart
data = pd.DataFrame({'Grade Category': np.tile(grade_categories, 3),
                     'Percentage': np.concatenate([grade_distribution_before, grade_distribution_during, grade_distribution_after]),
                     'Period': np.repeat(['Before COVID', 'During COVID', 'After COVID'], len(grade_categories))})

# Set the style for the plot
sns.set(style="whitegrid")

# Create a grouped bar chart with custom colors
palette = sns.color_palette("muted", 3)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))
bar_plot = sns.barplot(x='Grade Category', y='Percentage', hue='Period', data=data, palette=palette, ci=None)

# Customize the plot appearance
ax.set_ylabel('Percentage', fontsize=14)
ax.set_title('Grade Distribution Before, During, and After COVID', fontsize=16)
ax.set_xticklabels(grade_categories, rotation=45, ha='right', fontsize=12)
ax.legend(title='Period', title_fontsize=14, fontsize=12)

# Remove top and right spines for a cleaner look
sns.despine()

plt.show()

Surge in Top Grades¶

The analysis reveals that the overall increase in GPAs during the pandemic can be attributed to students obtaining A's at a considerably higher rate than before and after COVID. Interestingly, the proportion of students achieving A's did not revert to pre-pandemic levels in the post-COVID period.

While it is evident that students performed better in terms of GPAs during the pandemic compared to the periods before and after, this is only part of the story. Factors such as course withdrawals and drops can also influence the overall GPA outcomes. Consequently, it is worth investigating whether the increase in GPAs during the pandemic was driven by a higher number of course withdrawals.

In [6]:
courses_before_covid = courses_before_covid.copy()
courses_during_covid = courses_during_covid.copy()
courses_after_covid = courses_after_covid.copy()

# Calculate the withdraw rate for each period
courses_before_covid.loc[:, 'Withdraw Rate'] = courses_before_covid['Withdraws'] / courses_before_covid['Graded Enrollment']
courses_during_covid.loc[:, 'Withdraw Rate'] = courses_during_covid['Withdraws'] / courses_during_covid['Graded Enrollment']
courses_after_covid.loc[:, 'Withdraw Rate'] = courses_after_covid['Withdraws'] / courses_after_covid['Graded Enrollment']

# Calculate the average withdraw rate for each period
avg_withdraw_rate_before = courses_before_covid['Withdraw Rate'].mean()
avg_withdraw_rate_during = courses_during_covid['Withdraw Rate'].mean()
avg_withdraw_rate_after = courses_after_covid['Withdraw Rate'].mean()

# Plot the average withdraw rate for each period using an area plot
x_labels = ['Before COVID', 'During COVID', 'After COVID']
y_values = [avg_withdraw_rate_before, avg_withdraw_rate_during, avg_withdraw_rate_after]

# Create a DataFrame for the area plot
data = pd.DataFrame({'Period': x_labels, 'Average Withdraw Rate': y_values})

# Create the area plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
data.plot.area(x='Period', y='Average Withdraw Rate', ax=ax, alpha=0.3, legend=None)

# Customize the plot appearance
ax.set_ylabel('Average Withdraw Rate', fontsize=14)
ax.set_title('Average Withdraw Rate Before, During, and After COVID', fontsize=16)

# Remove top and right spines for a cleaner look
sns.despine()

plt.show()

Reduced Withdrawals¶

The analysis indicates that the rise in GPA during the pandemic was unlikely to be a result of increased course withdrawals. Surprisingly, students seemed more inclined to stay in their courses during the COVID period compared to the times before and after.

Since withdrawals do not appear to be the primary reason, I need to explore other factors that could have contributed to the increased GPA during the COVID-19 pandemic. One possible explanation is that students with minimal interest in their coursework may have opted not to return to Virginia Tech during the period of remote learning. This could have led to a shift in the overall student population, favoring those who were more motivated. To investigate this hypothesis, we should first examine the average enrollment for each time period.

A Slight Decline in Enrollment¶

Indeed, there seems to have been a minor dip in enrollment during the COVID-19 pandemic, but the decline was minimal and quickly recovered after the pandemic. Given the limited impact of this factor, it is necessary to consider other potential explanations for the increase in student GPA apart from the initial hypothesis about the nature of online work.

Is it possible that students enrolled in fewer high-credit courses, thereby reducing the workload and demands of each class?

Another Subtle Difference¶

It seems that there are actually more course credits taken across all course credit distributions post-COVID. During COVID, an increase of about 12,000 in the 3 credit hour category (the most common) can be observed from pre-COVID levels. However, this observation may not provide much insight, as various factors, such as increased enrollments and changes in the curriculum, could explain this difference.

Did the pandemic influence the GPA distribution across different subjects? Could the improvement in student performance be attributed to the selection of different classes? To answer this question, it is necessary to identify the most common courses taken before, during, and after COVID.

Minor Differences in Subjects Taken¶

There is very little difference in the breakdown of classes between the three time periods. The only distinction between during and before COVID is that communications no longer made the top ten class subjects taken during COVID and was replaced by ACIS.

However, a notable observation is the decrease in total course count during and after COVID compared to pre-COVID levels. It appears that almost all subjects had their course count halved during and post COVID. This seems to indicate that fewer courses were offered as the university consolidated the classes taught.

This leads to the next question: on a departmental basis, what is the difference between the pre-COVID and post-COVID GPA?

In [10]:
# Group by department and calculate mean GPA
mean_gpa_before_covid = courses_before_covid.groupby('Subject')['GPA'].mean().reset_index()
mean_gpa_during_covid = courses_during_covid.groupby('Subject')['GPA'].mean().reset_index()
mean_gpa_after_covid = courses_after_covid.groupby('Subject')['GPA'].mean().reset_index()

# Merge the results into a single dataframe
mean_gpa_all = mean_gpa_before_covid.merge(mean_gpa_during_covid, on='Subject', suffixes=('_before', '_during'))
mean_gpa_all = mean_gpa_all.merge(mean_gpa_after_covid, on='Subject')
mean_gpa_all.columns = ['Subject', 'Mean GPA Before COVID', 'Mean GPA During COVID', 'Mean GPA After COVID']

# Calculate the difference in mean GPA between before and during COVID
mean_gpa_all['GPA Difference'] = mean_gpa_all['Mean GPA During COVID'] - mean_gpa_all['Mean GPA Before COVID']

# Sort all departments by GPA Difference
all_departments_sorted = mean_gpa_all.sort_values('GPA Difference', ascending=False)

# Create a bar chart for all departments
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
sns.barplot(data=all_departments_sorted, x='Subject', y='GPA Difference')
plt.title('GPA Discrepancy by Department During COVID')
plt.xlabel('Department')
plt.ylabel('GPA Difference (During COVID - Before COVID)')
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.show()

GPA Difference¶

In line with previous analyses, it is evident that overall, GPA increased during the pandemic compared to pre-pandemic. Only a few departments experienced a lower average GPA.

Given that, what are the top ten departments with increases/decreases in GPA during COVID when compared to the pre-pandemic era?

In [11]:
# Calculate the difference in mean GPA between before and during COVID
mean_gpa_all['GPA Difference'] = mean_gpa_all['Mean GPA During COVID'] - mean_gpa_all['Mean GPA Before COVID']

# Sort by GPA Difference and separate into top 10 increased and top 10 decreased
top_10_increased = mean_gpa_all.nlargest(10, 'GPA Difference')
top_10_decreased = mean_gpa_all.nsmallest(10, 'GPA Difference')

# Function to create a bar chart for the top 10 departments
def plot_top_10_departments(data, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.barplot(data=data, x='Subject', y='GPA Difference')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel('Department')
    plt.ylabel('GPA Difference (During COVID - Before COVID)')
    plt.show()

# Create bar charts for the top 10 departments with increased and decreased GPA
plot_top_10_departments(top_10_increased, 'Top 10 Departments with Increased GPA During COVID')
plot_top_10_departments(top_10_decreased, 'Top 10 Departments with Decreased GPA During COVID')

STEM vs. People-Centered Studies¶

A general trend emerges: STEM classes made up the top ten courses with GPA increases, while classes centered around interactions among people (Hebrew, Military Science, Leadership) constituted the majority of classes that saw GPA decreases.

This raises the question: does this same trend persist after COVID?

mean_gpa_all = mean_gpa_before_covid.merge(mean_gpa_during_covid, on='Course Title', suffixes=('_before', '_during'))
mean_gpa_all = mean_gpa_all.merge(mean_gpa_after_covid, on='Course Title')
mean_gpa_all.columns = ['Course Title', 'Mean GPA Before COVID', 'Mean GPA During COVID', 'Mean GPA After COVID']

# Calculate the difference in mean GPA between before and during COVID
mean_gpa_all['GPA Difference'] = mean_gpa_all['Mean GPA During COVID'] - mean_gpa_all['Mean GPA Before COVID']

# Sort all departments by GPA Difference
all_departments_sorted = mean_gpa_all.sort_values('GPA Difference', ascending=False)

plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
sns.histplot(data=all_departments_sorted, x='GPA Difference', bins=30, palette='viridis', kde=True)
plt.title('GPA Discrepancy by Course During COVID')
plt.xlabel('GPA Difference (During COVID - Before COVID)')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.show()

import os

def plot_admissions_trends(csv_file, category='All'):
    # Read the CSV file
    df = pd.read_csv(os.path.join('Admissions', csv_file))
    
    # Transpose the dataframe and set column names
    df = df.T
    df.columns = df.iloc[0]
    df = df.iloc[1:]
    df.reset_index(inplace=True)
    df.rename(columns={'index': 'Year'}, inplace=True)
    
    # Calculate average differences before and after COVID
    pre_covid = df[df['Year'] <= '2020-21']
    post_covid = df[df['Year'] >= '2021-22']
    
    pre_covid_avg = pre_covid[['Applied', 'Offered', 'Enrolled']].mean()
    post_covid_avg = post_covid[['Applied', 'Offered', 'Enrolled']].mean()
    avg_difference = post_covid_avg - pre_covid_avg

    # Calculate offered rates for pre and post COVID
    pre_covid_offered_rate = (pre_covid['Offered'].astype(float) / pre_covid['Applied'].astype(float)).mean()
    post_covid_offered_rate = (post_covid['Offered'].astype(float) / post_covid['Applied'].astype(float)).mean()


    # Plot the trends
    plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))

    # Customize Seaborn style
    sns.set_style('darkgrid')
    sns.set_palette('tab10')

    # Line plots
    applied_plot = sns.lineplot(x='Year', y='Applied', data=df, label='Applied', marker='o', linewidth=2.5)
    offered_plot = sns.lineplot(x='Year', y='Offered', data=df, label='Offered', marker='o', linewidth=2.5)
    enrolled_plot = sns.lineplot(x='Year', y='Enrolled', data=df, label='Enrolled', marker='o', linewidth=2.5)

    # COVID vertical line (halfway between 2020-21 and 2021-22)
    covid_start_index = df[df['Year'] == '2020-21'].index[0] + 0.5
    plt.axvline(x=covid_start_index, color='red', linestyle='--', label='COVID-19 Start')
    
    # Add coordinate values
    for index, row in df.iterrows():
        plt.text(index - 0.3, row['Applied'] + 200, row['Applied'], fontsize=11, fontweight='bold')
        plt.text(index - 0.3, row['Offered'] - 600, row['Offered'], fontsize=11, fontweight='bold')
        plt.text(index - 0.3, row['Enrolled'] - 600, row['Enrolled'], fontsize=11, fontweight='bold')

    # Customize plot
    plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=14, labelpad=15)
    plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=14, labelpad=15)
    plt.title(f'{category} Student Admissions Trends', fontsize=18, pad=20)
    plt.xticks(df.index, df['Year'], rotation=45, fontsize=12)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=12)
    
    print(f"{category} - Pre COVID Offered Rate: {pre_covid_offered_rate:.2%}")
    print(f"{category} - Post COVID Offered Rate: {post_covid_offered_rate:.2%}")

    # Add average differences and offered rates to the legend
    legend_labels = [
        f"Applied (Δ: {avg_difference['Applied']:.2f})",
        f"Offered (Δ: {avg_difference['Offered']:.2f})",
        f"Enrolled (Δ: {avg_difference['Enrolled']:.2f})",
        'COVID-19 Start'
    ]

    handles, _ = plt.gca().get_legend_handles_labels()
    plt.legend(handles=handles, labels=legend_labels, fontsize=12)

    plt.show()
    
# Call the function with the example CSV file
plot_admissions_trends('Student_Admissions.csv', category='All')

All - Pre COVID Offered Rate: 69.17%
All - Post COVID Offered Rate: 56.73%

def plot_multiple_admissions_trends(csv_files, categories, title='Student Admissions Trends'):
    plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
    
    # Customize Seaborn style
    sns.set_style('darkgrid')
    sns.set_palette('tab10')

    legend_labels = []
    handles = []

    for csv_file, category in zip(csv_files, categories):
        # Read the CSV file
        df = pd.read_csv(os.path.join('Admissions', csv_file))
        
        # Transpose the dataframe and set column names
        df = df.T
        df.columns = df.iloc[0]
        df = df.iloc[1:]
        df.reset_index(inplace=True)
        df.rename(columns={'index': 'Year'}, inplace=True)
        
        # Calculate average differences before and after COVID
        pre_covid = df[df['Year'] <= '2020-21']
        post_covid = df[df['Year'] >= '2021-22']
        
        pre_covid_avg = pre_covid[['Applied', 'Offered', 'Enrolled']].mean()
        post_covid_avg = post_covid[['Applied', 'Offered', 'Enrolled']].mean()
        avg_difference = post_covid_avg - pre_covid_avg
        
        # Calculate offered rate for pre and post COVID
        pre_covid_offered_rate = (pre_covid['Offered'] / pre_covid['Applied']).mean() * 100
        post_covid_offered_rate = (post_covid['Offered'] / post_covid['Applied']).mean() * 100

        # Line plots with coordinate values
        for col in ['Applied', 'Offered', 'Enrolled']:
            plot = sns.lineplot(x='Year', y=col, data=df, marker='o', linewidth=2.5)
            handles.append(plot.lines[-1])
            legend_labels.append(f"{category} - {col} (Δ: {avg_difference[col]:.2f})")
            
            for index, row in df.iterrows():
                value = row[col]
                y_offset = 200 if col == 'Applied' else -600
                plt.text(index - 0.3, value + y_offset, int(value), fontsize=11, fontweight='bold')
    
        # Add offered rate for pre and post COVID to the legend
        print(f"{category} - Pre COVID Offered Rate: {pre_covid_offered_rate:.2f}%")
        print(f"{category} - Post COVID Offered Rate: {post_covid_offered_rate:.2f}%")
    
    # COVID vertical line (halfway between 2020-21 and 2021-22)
    covid_start_index = df[df['Year'] == '2020-21'].index[0] + 0.5
    plt.axvline(x=covid_start_index, color='red', linestyle='--', label='COVID-19 Start')
    handles.append(plt.gca().lines[-1])
    legend_labels.append('COVID-19 Start')
    
    # Customize plot
    plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=14, labelpad=15)
    plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=14, labelpad=15)
    plt.title(title, fontsize=18, pad=20)
    plt.xticks(df.index, df['Year'], rotation=45, fontsize=12)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=12)

    # Add average differences to the legend
    plt.legend(handles=handles, labels=legend_labels, fontsize=12)

    plt.show()

csv_files = ['Male_Admissions.csv', 'Female_Admissions.csv']

On the whole, Virginia Tech's student population became less Virginian after COVID-19. This is further evidenced by the difference in offer rates post-COVID: 46.8% for an in-state student, 64.6% for an out of state student.

Steady Increases in Applications from All Races, But Decreases in Acceptance Rates for Some¶

All races (White, Black, Hispanic, and Asian) saw increases in application numbers post-COVID, but their distributions were not all the same.

White¶

There was an increase of 1500 offers post-COVID to White students. This is despite White students' acceptance rate falling 14% when compared to pre-COVID rates (down from 71%). Keeping in line with the reduction in acceptance rate, however, was the enrollment: 135 fewer White students enrolled at Virginia Tech post-pandemic.

Black¶

There was a significant increase in the number of Black students applying to Virginia Tech post-pandemic, with applications increasing by roughly 1900. This led to an increase in offers (1000) and enrollments (181) when compared to pre-pandemic numbers. Additionally, the overall acceptance rate for Black students increased by 2%, up from 56%.

Hispanic¶

Hispanic students also saw an increase in applications, offers, and enrollments, with similar numbers to African-American students (roughly 1800 more applications, 1250 more offers, and 270 more enrollments when compared with pre-pandemic numbers). The acceptance rate of Hispanic students also increased post-COVID by 2%, up from 66%.

Asian¶

Asian students had the largest increase in number of applications by minority groups, and also saw an increase in offers and enrollments (roughly 2900 more applications, 1230 more offers, and 153 more enrollments). Interestly, though, they also saw their acceptance rate decrease by 12%, down from 67%.

On the whole, it appears that COVID-19 made Virginia Tech into a much more racially and ethnically diverse university.

Conclusion Iteration 1¶

How has remote learning affected students' academic performance during the pandemic? The overall grades increased from a 3.39 GPA before to a 3.49 GPA during the pandemic, reflecting a 0.1 GPA increase. Additionally, the withdrawal rate from classes significantly decreased, suggesting that students adapted well to their new learning environments even during a global pandemic. When classes returned to classrooms, how did class GPAs fare? Class GPAs overall after the pandemic were 0.02 GPA lower than during the pandemic. Interestingly, however, the GPAs after the pandemic (3.42) did not return to the same level as before the pandemic (3.39). This could indicate that the transition to virtual learning not only improved student performance in classes but also enhanced the quality of classes taught by the professors.

It is worth noting that there was a higher amount of course withdrawals after the pandemic, with the difference being 1.2%. As the GPA does not provide an accurate representation since a withdrawal grade omits the course's GPA, this increase in withdrawals excludes a large portion of students, thereby presenting a more favorable GPA since the mean GPA of students after the pandemic was 0.03 higher than before the pandemic. The analysis also employs only the mean metric for GPA calculations, with other metrics such as median or mode being excluded. Incorporating the median for further calculations could potentially eliminate skew from the GPA discrepancy calculations before and after the pandemic. Demonstrating the skewed data from the median could reveal that the GPA discrepancy is higher, implying that the number of courses with a positive increase in grades is greater after the pandemic than during the pandemic.

Follow-up questions: How would the increase in the number of withdrawals change the mean GPA? What is the change in GPA for only engineering majors (categorize the majors in these clusters)? When were grades the highest?

Conclusion Iteration 2¶

How has the pandemic affected the transition to higher education for high school graduates? The pandemic has witnessed an increase in application numbers from 30,770 students to 42,054 students, but this increase has not been equally distributed among the diversity of students. For instance, Black and Hispanic students have experienced an increase in acceptance rates with about a 2% increase, while White and Asian students have seen a significant decrease, between 12-14%. This can be interpreted as an increase in Virginia Tech's diversity post-pandemic. Consequently, the overall trend post-pandemic and on return from the pandemic has shown a positive trend in applications, offers, and enrollments. The increase in applications could be a result of people having more time during quarantine, thus applying to more colleges. The increase in offers is a direct correlation with the number of applications and possibly more room for each class with the shift to online courses.

Follow-up questions: How has quarantine affected application numbers?
